      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A 3-year-old child was brought to the ER with metabolic acidosis after accidental ingestion of flavoured aspirin tablets of an unknown quantity. Her blood pH - 7.0, pKa of aspirin - 3, calculate the ratio of its ionized to unionized forms at the same pH 7.0.</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q8751398",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30069,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. B. 10,000 to 1</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">This question requires application of the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation to determine the ratio of ionized to unionized forms of aspirin at a given pH.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The Henderson-Hasselbalch equation is: pH = pKa + log([A⁻]/[HA])</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Where:</strong></span></p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">[A⁻] represents the concentration of the ionized (deprotonated) form</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">[HA] represents the concentration of the unionized (protonated) form</span></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Given:</strong></span></p><ul style=\"list-style-type:disc;\"><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">pH = 7.0</span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">pKa of aspirin = 3.0</span></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img class=\"image_resized\" style=\"aspect-ratio:680/463;width:60.47%;\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/Screenshot%202025-05-14%20115736.png\" width=\"680\" height=\"463\"></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Log 10<sup>1</sup> = 1</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Log 10<sup>2</sup> = 2</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Log 10<sup>3</sup> = 3</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Log 10<sup>4</sup> = 4</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">So, the ratio of ionized to unionized aspirin is <strong>10,000:1</strong> at pH 7.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">\"The Henderson-Hasselbalch equation permits calculation of the ratio of ionized to unionized species for a weak acid at any given pH.\"</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Ref: Lippincott 7/e: p 6-10.</span></p>",
