      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">In a renal physiology session, medical residents are discussing various methods to evaluate kidney function. One resident mentions a substance used in a specific clearance test that accurately measures the glomerular filtration rate (GFR), which is essential for assessing renal function. The residents are asked to identify the substance used in this gold-standard test for GFR assessment. Which of the following substances is used to measure GFR through its clearance rate?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q8777205",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30068,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. C) Inulin</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Inulin</strong> clearance is considered the <strong>gold standard </strong>for measuring the<strong> glomerular filtration rate (GFR)</strong> because <strong>inulin </strong>is freely filtered at the <strong>glomerulus</strong> and is <strong>neither</strong> <strong>reabsorbed nor secreted</strong> by the <strong>renal tubules</strong>. This makes it an <strong>ideal </strong>marker for assessing the<strong> filtration capacity </strong>of the <strong>kidneys.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A. Creatinine:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> While<strong> creatinine clearance</strong> is commonly used in clinical practice to <strong>estimate GFR </strong>due to <strong>its practicality</strong>, it is <strong>not</strong> as accurate as <strong>inulin clearance</strong> because <strong>creatinine</strong> is slightly <strong>secreted by the renal tubules</strong> in addition to <strong>being filtered </strong>by the <strong>glomerulus.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B. Urea:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>Urea clearance</strong> is<strong> not</strong> an accurate measure of <strong>GFR</strong> because urea is <strong>both reabsorbed and secreted</strong> by the <strong>renal</strong> <strong>tubules.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D. Albumin:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> Albumin is a <strong>large protein </strong>that is normally <strong>not </strong>filtered by the <strong>glomerulus </strong>in significant amounts due to <strong>its size </strong>and <strong>charge</strong>; thus, it is <strong>not </strong>used to <strong>measure GFR.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Inulin </strong>is a <strong>polysaccharide of fructose </strong>and is <strong>not </strong>appreciably <strong>metabolized </strong>by the <strong>body</strong>. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">It is<strong> neither absorbed nor secreted </strong>by the <strong>tubules </strong>&rarr;Hence, it is a <strong>measure of GFR. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The value of <strong>GFR </strong>as measured by <strong>inulin clearance </strong>is <strong>125 mL/min.</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: DM Vasudevan 9/e: p 418.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
